 {"id":"bd-36l.5","title":"Separate is_closed() from is_tombstone() in status semantics","description":"Go distinguishes IsClosed() (only 'closed') from IsTombstone() (only 'tombstone'), while Rust's is_closed_like() treats BOTH as closed. This affects issue counting: tombstoned issues shouldn't appear in 'closed' counts, they're permanently removed records. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) In src/model.rs, split is_closed_like() into is_closed() (status == 'closed'), is_tombstone() (status == 'tombstone'), and is_terminal() (either). (2) Update call sites: analysis/graph counting should use is_terminal() (neither open nor working). Triage counts should distinguish. Robot output counts (open/closed/tombstone) should be separate. (3) Keep is_open_like() as \!is_terminal() for backward compat. Go ref: pkg/model/types.go Status.IsClosed(), Status.IsTombstone(). ACCEPTANCE: is_closed() returns false for tombstone. Separate counts in triage output.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:53.347363059Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T03:49:48.435730353Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T03:49:48.434833193Z","close_reason":"Added is_closed() and is_tombstone() methods to Issue model. is_closed_like() retained as terminal status check. SnapshotCounts in diff.rs now tracks tombstone separately with terminal() accessor. 1 new unit test. 474 lib tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:53.347363059Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":25,"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/model/issue.go — is_closed() means work is done. is_tombstone() means the issue was deleted/merged/superseded. Currently Rust treats both the same (any non-open status). The distinction matters for metrics — tombstoned issues shouldn't count in veloci